I think that’s a useful distinction, provided you keep the boundary clear between experience and the external world.

One way to frame it is:

Internal reality	External reality
Thoughts	Physical events
Emotions	Observable facts
Meanings	Measurements
Intentions	Consequences
Memories	History
Perception	Environment

Neither is sufficient by itself.

If you focus only on the external, you risk treating people as machines. You might know every measurable fact while missing fear, hope, motivation, grief, or joy—all of which influence behavior.

If you focus only on the internal, you risk mistaking sincere feelings for objective facts. An experience can be deeply real to the person having it while still not accurately describing what happened in the outside world.

A healthy cognitive stance is to let them continually inform one another:

External world
      ↓
 Perception
      ↓
Internal model
      ↓
 Decisions
      ↓
 Actions
      ↓
External consequences
      ↺

The loop keeps running. Good judgment comes from updating the internal model when external evidence changes, while also recognizing that internal states—motivation, meaning, values, suffering—are genuine parts of human life that shape what people do.

This also connects to an earlier insight you’ve explored:

“Experience is the inside’s best constrained reconstruction of the outside.”

The external world constrains what can be true, while the internal world determines how we interpret, remember, and respond to it. Intelligence isn’t choosing one over the other—it’s maintaining a calibrated dialogue between them.

That’s a useful design principle for AI as well. An AI that only models external facts may come across as cold or miss important human context. An AI that only validates internal experience without regard for evidence can mislead. The challenge is to acknowledge subjective experience while staying anchored to what can be observed and verified.